<DOC><DOCNO>WSJ900904-0092</DOCNO><DOCID>900904-0092.</DOCID><HL>   Martin Marietta Pays Out   $2,565,377 to Settle Case</HL><DATE>09/04/90</DATE><SO>WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE C5</SO><CO>   ML</CO><IN>AEROSPACE (ARO)</IN><GV>JUSTICE DEPARTMENT (JUS)DEFENSE DEPARTMENT (DEF)</GV><LP>   WASHINGTON -- Martin Marietta Corp. paid an additional$2,565,377 to settle civil charges that its Martin MariettaElectronics andamp; Missiles Group overcharged the government foruse of computer facilities, the Justice Department said.   The company earlier had paid $898,000 to settle part ofthe case, which began when the company voluntarily disclosedthe problem in September 1986. The Justice Department said aninvestigation by the Defense Criminal Investigative Servicefound that the Martin Marietta unit provided inflated costdata and as a result received more money than it should have.</LP><TEXT>   The unit had disclosed that it overcharged the governmentfor use of its Technical Computation Center, and hascooperated with the investigation, the Justice Departmentsaid. Since disclosing the problem, Martin Marietta has takencorrective actions, including dismissing employees who werefound responsible, improving reporting and billingprocedures, and increasing its training and internal audits,a company spokesman said.</TEXT></DOC>